name: Will Buxton
tweet: @ChemistryKit Yeah. I took it as a WDC being beaten to the title by a driver with no WDCs. Fun to look back, though...

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @ChemistryKit To be beaten, I'd suppose you'd have to have been active. Rindt couldn't defend his crown as he took it posthumously. Ascari lost the title in 54 to Fangio for his 2nd, and was killed in 55, so was never active and beaten by a 1st timer. Hawthorn, Hakkinen and NRosberg retired.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Mansell didn't defend his crown in 93, but did return to race in 94 where he was beaten by Schumacher taking his first. Does he count as he didn't contest the full season? Arguably a 6th for the list.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Of the hot takes posted today, This one takes some beating.   (And with thanks to twitter for correcting & improving my initial tweet...)  Ascari, Hawthorn, Rindt, Hakkinen and N. Rosberg are the only drivers who weren't beaten to the WDC by a driver taking their first.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @DanielG06251142 So that was a follow up tweet. Obviously came back in 94 so was beaten by Schumacher but it wasn't a full season. Definite list of 4. Mansell potential 5th.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Damn, yes. Correct, of course. I even had it written down. Apologies.  So 4: Ascari, Rindt, Hawthorn and Nico Rosberg.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Mansell is a potential fourth, if you exclude his few races standing in at Williams in 94. Otherwise Schumacher took his first while Mansell was still active.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @neilhamshaw @F1 No Barcelona test last year either. Testing was reduced to 3 days from 21 moving forward. The 3 days of shakedown at least mean those who can attend or watch the live action from Bahrain on TV will do so to hopefully a full track of functioning cars.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @manueljerez7_ How? Nobody has ever attended shakedowns. Not fans. Not media. They've always been strictly private affairs. Now the shakedowns are all happening at once and there'll be coverage of them from the ground.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: With testing restricted to 3 days from 2021, good to see that the teams will all come together for an important 3 day shakedown of the new cars ahead of the pre-season test in Bahrain. While shakedowns are usually private, also positive that media can attend to provide updates.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @hawkeye_mbg As I understand it, Barcelona is more of a shakedown than a full test. Testing was held over 3 days in 2021 in Bahrain and will continue to be in 2022. Shakedowns are usually held in private but getting everyone together for one big shakedown should reduce costs for all.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: The ruling today, however, is not that the decision in Brazil was correct or incorrect. But merely that the right to review has failed. That’s a really key and important distinction.   It should be read for what it is.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Having shone a light on the incident there is reason to believe that similar incidents might be judged with greater scrutiny and that should the prevailing opinion be that a clearer precedent needs to be set, it will be.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: For all those saying Brazil does now create a precedent that pushing drivers off track is OK, the rejection of the right to review does not say that what was decided in Brazil was correct. Merely that the “new evidence” wasn’t “significant” enough to allow an appeal.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Qatar proving to be very tough on F1 cars. Mazepin ruled out of FP2  as he requires a chassis change due to damage picked up in FP1.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Should probably clarify that the forward facing camera doesn’t change that in so much as it isn’t considered grounds enough to permit an appeal to be heard.   Either way, the rejection of the right to appeal absolutely does not legitimise pushing a driver off track.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Before this place descends into the expected dumpster fire, this absolutely does not legitimise pushing a driver off track. Merely that the stewards didn’t think the action in Brazil passed the test of what was punishable and the forward facing camera doesn’t change that.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @BradleyPhilpot @Jontys_Corner @elpresidente54 Ultimately we are still getting ahead of ourselves.   First thing is to see whether the Mercedes appeal will even be heard, and whether new evidence can be submitted for an investigation that arguably never took place.   If it is, then this nuanced argument will be debated.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @Jontys_Corner @elpresidente54 @BradleyPhilpot Of course. It’s completely intentional. But it’s borderline whether it’s illegal. “Racing room” isn’t firmly entrenched in the rules. Crowding seemingly is. But with Hamilton being wise to the defense and ducking out, it’s arguable if he was, in fact, crowded.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @Jontys_Corner @elpresidente54 @BradleyPhilpot Because it was a measured defense rather than a locked up Hail Mary. You have to be able to defend but you can’t elbow someone off by crowding. Had Lewis carried more speed and stayed side by side, ive already said I think it’s a slam dunk. That he didn’t ultimately led to debate

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @elpresidente54 @BradleyPhilpot @Jontys_Corner It’s called a difference of opinion. One to which we are all entitled. If you genuinely believed some mysterious edict goes out after this kind of thing we’d all be pushing the same narrative. Which we are not. Because we can all form our own opinions and agree to disagree.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: But if you fervently believe that Verstappen should have been penalised in Brazil, and you want to use precedent as your reasoning, then you cannot, with any semblance of a shred of good will or sincerity, argue Hamilton did not at Silverstone.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Each move has to be judged alone. It gets incredibly murky if you start to take previous examples, at different tracks, on different corners, at different speeds, as your sole reasoning for the apportioning blame on a move which is, by its nature, entirely different.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: For what it's worth I still think that race control / the stewards got things right at both Silverstone and Brazil as regards the HAM/VER incidents. Race manoeuvres are unique and have to be judged as such. Precedent can aid as much as hinder an objective view.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Racing manoeuvres are rarely black and white. They are unique and exist in the grey areas. If they were slam dunks, there’d be no need for discussion.   Factional fanaticism and the notion of rationally debating right and wrong don’t coexist happily. Especially online. Sadly.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: For me it’s close. Possibly too close to call. All I can say is I’m glad there was no call and it was ultimately decided on track by a supreme pass. That’s what we all want to see. Not a race decided by a penalty.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Studied the onboard from Max’s car this morning along with data traces from both cars for Weekend Debrief on F1TV. It’s hard racing, but Verstappen is in control. Crowding is debatable. Question of whether at the pace and turn in Ham would have made the corner anyway. Intriguing.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: And yes… the version we have on the Super Deluxe is a mishmash of 69/70 cuts of Glyn’s work. (Japanese edition is reportedly a full 69 version). But the feeling and intention of what he was trying to create is clear throughout. I love it.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: There’s a feeling of brotherhood, friendship, levity and love that sweeps over the whole thing. There’s humour, feeling and soul. Glyn Johns’ album might have created a completely different narrative in @thebeatles breakup story we’ve lived with for 50 years.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: I can see why it was rejected. It’s disjointed. But it’s sad that it was. The original intention of the album was to “Get Back” to basics. There’s no more initiate version than this. It puts you in the studio and at the heart of the band. It’s a real fly on the wall.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: I’ve always found Spector’s “Let it Be” to be cold. As Martin said, he produced it, Spector “over produced” it. Even the “Naked” version without the Wall of Sound is quite polished. Glyn John’s’ version is a completely different imagining of the album.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Beatles nerds will know all about it but for those new to the story, Glyn was a sound engineer and producer originally brought in to save the project. Way before the George Martin and Phil Spector mixes of what would become “Let it Be,” Glyn gave it quite a few attempts.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Of everything brilliant to come out pre release of Peter Jackson’s “Get Back” the Super Deluxe edition of @thebeatles ”Let it Be” features one of Glyn John’s’ original edits of a “Get Back” album and it is glorious.  https://t.co/tRFKyyxcVJ

tweet: Well that was fantastic fun. My first lead commentary in 7 years and my first ever on F1. Calling the PLC triple box layout was one of the hardest things I’ve ever done. But I loved it. Thanks to @NorthHertsSam, @42jordanking and all the gang on F1TV. And to you all for watching.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: That said, it doesn’t mean they have to rejoin the track straight away. They could still straight line the corner and cut inside the bollard.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: The only logic I can see behind this is that a driver straight lining T1 and re-entering at T3 is likely to make up a LOT of positions. Giving them back could prove a logistical nightmare.   That said, this last minute change could see contact and controversy at race start.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: FIA update on driver etiquette issued while drivers are on driver parade. At the start those running off at T1 won’t have to use T3 bollard for re-entry. Can re-enter safely ASAP. Any positions gained must be given back. Any crowding off anywhere directed to stewards all race.

tweet: Very excited for today’s race. Quite incredibly, this will be my first ever F1 race on lead commentary. Do join @42jordanking, @NorthHertsSam and I, if you can, on the @F1TV Pitlane channel. Can’t wait to see you there.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: TE Lawrence (of Arabia) lost his life riding home from the Bovington base. He was attended to by Australian Hugh Cairns, one of the UK’s first neurosurgeons and pioneering medics. He would dedicate his life to advocating for the mandatory use of crash helmets on motorbikes.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Bovington is a great location for Extreme E. It’s forested heathland which plays home to the British Armed Forces armoured divisions and due to the challenging nature of the terrain is used extensively to train tank drivers. Home to the Tank Museum too which is ace!

name: Will Buxton
tweet: So the question I guess we are left with is whether any penalty needed to be given, if racing incidents can still just be racing incidents when it involves championship rivals, and in this case if not, whether blame was apportioned correctly and proportionately.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: There’s every justification that this was simply a racing incident. And if not, that Hamilton as the driver re-entering the track, the aggressor and the one who needed to pull the pass off and who closed the door mid pass was more at fault. Again, it’s arguable.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Could max have backed out and cut to the left across the speed bumps? Yes. Should he have needed to? Arguably not. 50/50? Again, arguably. 60/40 against Hamilton given he closed the door with Max alongside? Again, that’s arguable.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: But this is where it gets sketchy… there’s space for two cars at T2 but the driver who now finds himself on the outside has to give space. A lot of space. Hamilton says he did. The images suggest otherwise.  https://t.co/4jtikcFk2p

name: Will Buxton
tweet: The two navigate Turn 1 side by side and cleanly. The onus is still on Lewis as the aggressor to pull the move off, and Max is entitled to defend his position which he does by running a touch faster and deeper.  https://t.co/L4OVvltt68

name: Will Buxton
tweet: If we rewind a few years, Hamilton was left less than impressed with Leclerc squeezing him in a similar style, in an incident which bought Charles a black and white warning flag. There’s precedent therefore that Hamilton was, perhaps, a bit naughty on Sunday under braking.  https://t.co/5nl6WAiWac

name: Will Buxton
tweet: After the blend line finishes, Hamilton moves onto the racing line in the braking zone. At this point and given he’s been shown the blue, the onus is still on him. Yet Verstappen isn’t wholly behind and so he should give a cars width, which he does not.  https://t.co/SKvIRs4ZAc

name: Will Buxton
tweet: When a driver leaves the pits and other cars are on the straight, the driver exiting is shown a blue light at pit exit and a blue flag is waved as shown here. This is because the onus is on them not to cede position but to re-enter the track mindfully.  https://t.co/cKkCf5mDP6

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Even if Martins completed his overtake within track limits, the initial move at Jacky Ickx corner (nobody calls it that, it's still known as "the corner with no name" or "speakers corner") was well outside and so the "lasting advantage" edict would have stood. Great F3 race.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: True but they did change the corner. Vialone was a flat out left hander. When it was changed to the left right left for 1972 it was renamed Ascari. As I understand it Parabolica will remain the same corner in all but name.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: People will still call Parabolica, Parabolica. Just as they still call the last chicane here at Spa "Bus Stop," even though it isn't anymore. Which sort of undermines the intention of a tribute to a racing driver in Michele who deserves such a recognition.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: While naming a corner for Michele Alboreto is long past due, I do find it strange that Monza should have chosen to rename a corner with the history and public attachment of Parabolica. Surely the two Variantes della Roggia and del Rettifilio would have been missed less.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @harrismonkey Absolutely. But if your move is working and you find yourself alongside then you absolutely should have an equal right to racing room as the driver you're trying to pass.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Interstingly, I've seen folks getting quite angry about the fact I used the regulations to back up this argument yesterday. (Sporting Code Appendix L). The rules are there for a reason. Everyone knows them. They shouldn't be surprised that they get penalised when they break them.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Personally I've never been a fan of crowding / edging another driver out of room in a corner. To my mind it isn't "hard racing." You don't see it in Indycar. You don't see it in NASCAR. Because if you don't run 2 or 3 wide with respect for each other over there, people get hurt.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: This isn't making overtaking easy. It isn't making defending impossible. It's simply reinforcing the requirement for racing room. And ultimately that all comes down to respect and racecraft.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: And the "he's just following the racing line" argument doesn't wash either. If the lead driver was on the racing line at T4, the inside line is the only way through. For an outside pass to be possible, the lead driver has to have changed line and gone defensive already.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: But just as shoving your nose up the inside doesn't guarantee a pass, neither does having a sniff around the outside. You've got to be alongside or marginally ahead at some point of the corner (braking zone included) to be judged as being owed that racing room.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Let's imagine the move was on the inside. If the attacking driver had managed to get up and level and the lead driver slammed the door shut to such an extent that the attacker was pushed off the track... again, you'd say slam dunk penalty.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: When the attacking car is substantially alongside, racing room has to be given. This is as true in corners as it is on straights. If the leading car edged the attacking car off track on a straight it's a slam dunk penalty. The same goes in corners. You can't just run people off.

name: Will Buxton

tweet: Recall any great livery and you instantly recall the sponsor attached to it. That’s how marketing works. That’s what pulls in the $$. And that’s what allows the investment in the departments that do make the car go fast.   A pretty paint job isn’t as frivolous as can be made out.

tweet: In light of the debate sparked by Colton Herta’s stunning St Pete weekend, why I sadly don’t think we’ll see an American Indycar crossover anytime soon...    https://t.co/pmmYFD7UB8

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Perhaps the new F1 car and budget cap might make the crossover more viable. If the championship gives more opportunity for success, there’s more chance a Ganassi, Penske or an Andretti driver considering an Aston or an Alpine or an Alfa Romeo might be worth the switch.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Ultimately, the question might actually be misplaced...   Why would an Indycar driver give up racing in a series where they have a chance to win every weekend, to race for a team in F1 that doesn’t? Because unless the call comes in from the top 3 in F1... why leave?

name: Will Buxton
tweet: As any F1 driver who has made the switch will tell you (@RGrosjean, @Ericsson_Marcus , @AlexanderRossi to name a few in recent years) Indycar has one of the highest levels of racer in any category on earth.   So why the reluctance? What’s stopping the crossover?

name: Will Buxton
tweet: There’s going to be a lot of talk about this. The irony is Colton DOES qualify for a superlicense. Beyond the obvious question of why Indycar is rewarded with fewer SL points than F2, the bigger question is why F1 teams are reluctant to give supreme Indycar talent a chance?

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @MrDavidHobbs @MarioAndretti @ColtonHerta I’ll admit that in my eyes Indycar’s weighting in SL points should be brought up to F2 levels.  Eligibility isn’t the issue though. He’s in the same system as everyone else. I really don’t like the points system but Colton qualifies.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @MrDavidHobbs @MarioAndretti @ColtonHerta Colton is eligible though mon ami. Any driver is eligible so long as they have the points.   Over past 3 years Colton has 39 but needs 40 for a SL. But FIA made a provision under Covid for best 3 of past 4 years which gives him 45 points. Ample.   He qualifies.

tweet: @Liam_Redford @X44Racing @jbxnn23 But it’s the not knowing that’s the issue, isn’t it.   Sure you’re free not to test.   You’re free not to have your bags checked at the airport.   You just won’t be getting on the plane.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Even if you only tested when you wanted to go out... adding £75 to the price of a theatre ticket or restaurant bill (per head), is cost prohibitive.   While the act of testing has, for me, become very normal and allowed work life to continue, costs for real life have to come down

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @stephg40 No and as I’ve followed up that’s a massive consideration. 5k a year if we were all to be tested weekly just isn’t feasible.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Cost is a huge barrier though... if any notion of the reopening of the entertainment sector is to be based on negative testing the price point at present is just too high. If we all tested weekly, we’d be between £4K-5k per person per year. That’s just unimaginable.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: I don’t think I’d fully appreciated quite how normal the idea of PCR tests has become to me. I lost count at 57 last year. Well over one a week. They’ve allowed work to carry on as close to what we knew before as possible. They’re no longer an annoyance. They’re just... life.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @m_a_sumner Pretty similar. Back of the throat, up your nose, scoop out a bit of your brain, make you cry.   Repeat.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @Liam_Redford Metal detectors at airports are there to protect fellow passengers. To ensue someone isn’t putting others at risk. The requirement of a negative PCR test to enter a show would be the same. I don’t see that as a removal of liberty.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @Liam_Redford Where do you stand on metal detectors at airports?

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @_Clare_B_ That’s critically important

name: Will Buxton
tweet: I’d agree vaccination passports wouldn’t restrict transmission and with vaccines not available to all could be seen as divisive and discriminatory... but taking a PCR test and showing a QR code along with your ticket for a show, your restaurant reservation... no issues for me.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: If all it takes is a negative PCR test to be happily put on a giant sealed metal tube in the sky with hundreds of people for 6 hours, I’d take as many swabs in my face as you could fit if it meant the return of gigs, festivals, theatre... culture... life!!!

name: Will Buxton
tweet: After an exhilarating first race of the season, track limits are headline news again. But how did the events of the weekend unfold, and why were there essentially two rules in play for one piece of off-track asphalt?    https://t.co/iEcfVg1x8b

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @maginleym Matthew I've been following the sport all my life and reporting on it for 20. I have the exact same question.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @LucasdiGrassi Yep. Love it.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @willyumclarke @fia I’m only using the drivers to illustrate a point.   Driver A shouldn’t be allowed to drive off track to the benefit of their lap time if driver B can’t use that same piece of land to overtake. It’s usable territory or it isn’t.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: This is a really interesting one.   Was he only ahead because he carried too much speed which caused him to go off track?   Was he legitimately ahead and Lewis forced him off track?   Fascinating debate

name: Will Buxton
tweet: That is why, to my mind, you cannot allow differing rules pertaining to track limits, based in nuance and perceptible grey areas.   Black and white. Right and wrong.   Four wheels over.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: The argument, to which I subscribe, is you cannot call one permissible and the other not. If you’re allowed to run there alone it’s part of the track and you can pass there. If you can’t pass there it’s not part of the track and driving on it should be penalised at all times.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: To be clear on the issue of running over the white lines... it’s not about Max’s pass. It occurred off track. It doesn’t count.   It’s about the almost 30 occasions on which Lewis did the same when alone. Each occurrence was arguably an advantage. Which lasted.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @NorthHertsSam And that’s the point mate.   If track limits exist then you can’t overtake off track because off track isn’t the race track.   It’s really simple. Multiple rules of what you can and can’t do offtrack needn’t exist if you simply dictate that you need to stay on track.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: @NorthHertsSam But that’s the issue isn’t it. Enforce them or don’t. There shouldn’t be a grey area. If you’re only enforcing the rule when a pass is made that contravenes them then they are enforced only in part.   Black or white. It’s the only way to avoid this.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Track limits.   The problem, as I've always seen it, is that the second you make allowances, you create the opportunity for confusion and inconsistency.   All four wheels over the line is either permitted or its not.   It needs to be black and white.   You can't be half pregnant.

tweet: F2 / GP2's sprint race historically came after the feature with the grid featuring an inversion of some type for the top points scorers in the main event.   If sprint races are to be a thing in F1, I like what F2 is doing. Something fun for the sprint, serious for the main event.

tweet: For reference, F2 features 3 races this season. There'll be one more sprint race today with the grid formed from the results of this first sprint race, with the top 10 inverted, with the main feature race grid formed from the actual results of original qualifying.

tweet: In short then, it's not all part of some devious masterplan as a few rival teams had feared.   It's a genuine filming day for content capture.   The troublesome test run has discovered the "hair in the soup," as Toto put it. The team has a week to fix it.   Game on.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: And of course there's Romain's accident, set amidst the swirling uncertainties at the end of the year. The gravity and severity of the crash are tempered with some touching and at times humorous asides from Romain and Marion, which only serve to reinforce a racer's humanity.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: The Racing Point saga is dealt with well, spread over a few episodes, and makes what was a complex situation manageable for a new audience without skirting too lightly for die hards. The second Red Bull seat and the Pierre / Alex storyline is also nicely handled.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: The Mercedes episode is incredibly heartfelt and human, with a real gut punch ending. The Ferrari episode is also brilliantly and unexpectedly candid as the team's relationship with Sebastian deteriorates. A conversation between Seb and Christian Horner is a real wow moment, too.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: With the embargo lifted today on reviews for season 3 of Drive to Survive, I can honestly so it's the best so far. The consistency across the series as a whole and the quality of the story telling is outstanding. The Mercedes and Ferrari episodes in particular are excellent.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Essentially, as things stand, anything less than a 30 second penalty, and it doesn't matter for the championship. McLaren take P3.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: 10 laps to go.   If Sainz does get a post race penalty, in lieu of a drive-through penalty he'd have 20 seconds added, and thirty seconds in the case of stop-go penalty.    Scenario 1, McLaren would still likely have P3.  Scenario 2, RP could still be in the fight.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Despite his new tyres, Ricciardo is falling off. Now 17 seconds back from Sainz and dropping.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Ricciardo stops and emerges 14 seconds behind the McLarens.  McLaren +18, RP +2  McLaren P3 by 6 points

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Vettel stops, and Stroll is back in 9th but having lost 8 seconds to Gasly in the intervening period.   McLaren +14, RP +2  McLaren P3 by 2 points

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Stroll meanwhile loses 9th to Gasly. McLaren +14, RP + 1. McLaren have P3 by 3 points   Until we have a resolution from stewards of pitlane infringement

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Sainz pitlane incident will be investigated post race. @NorthHertsSam has all the evidence of what happened and how and we'll be debating it on the #F1Live post race show. Only 3rd place in the constructors to be decided. No pressure...

name: Will Buxton
tweet: If Seb wanted to help his new team out, he could make life easy for Stroll, but the RP driver isn't anywhere near close enough. Runs wide pushing to catch his future team-mate.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Stroll finally makes it work on Leclerc. McLaren now +14, RP +2... it's McLaren's P3 by 2 points.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: As Stroll fails to make a move in Leclerc stick, Sainz gets by Vettel to give McLaren a 3 point advantage for P3. BUT he's under investigation for driving slowly in the pitlane.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Carlos' move on Leclerc slides McLaren into P3 by 1 point

name: Will Buxton
tweet: After the stops, Racing Point are on for 3rd by a point. If Stroll gets an unsafe release and drops out of points, it's still RP's on countback. But there is a LONG way to go.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Ah man that is galling for Perez. Out of his final race for Racing Point. Huge potential swing in battle for P3 in constructors' too.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: This is one of the most important afternoons of Stroll's career so far. Carrying the team's hopes of third, he's got to step up to the plate. 10 laps in, McLaren are on to take 3rd by 4 points. Perez on the alternate strategy, starting on hard, is up to P14.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Off to sleep tonight delighted for @SChecoPerez. Some people feel I have some negativity towards him (thanks to some editing in DTS season 1) but I’ve always adored his race craft and held a great personal relationship with him.   Nobody deserves this more.   Felicidades amigo.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Read this thread. All of it.   Truth from a racer who knows.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: The problem with social media and online debate is that there’s no space for the grey. It’s a world of absolutes. It’s one thing or the other. Black or white. But life doesn’t work like that. Neither does F1. Great car and great driver. If 1 part is lacking so is the outcome.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: There will be a debate tonight over Russell’s race and whether it undermines Hamilton’s success. Ultimately I think it reinforces Russell’s pedigree. There will still be those who say “it’s all car.” The truth, as always, lies in nuance and the grey areas.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Two of the most likeable and talented racers in the field. Both experiencing their first wins in the midst of their best ever seasons.   It is the ultimate vindication and validation of all they hold dear. And all they always knew that they were.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: That is to say, there is some heavy weight chatter in the paddock tonight of news breaking in the coming days over Checo's future. With any luck, we will be talking about it on the Weekend Warmup on Thursday.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: In all the madness of that race, a huge shout to the brilliant @OconEsteban. He was always going to find his feet at Renault, and when he did the results were going to come. Wonderful to see him back on a podium and smiling so brightly. Bravo.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: That win wasn't just validation or vindication for @SChecoPerez, it was the clearest example of why he HAS to stay in the sport next season. And from my disappointed pessimism just 48 hours ago, I've been convinced this evening that everything is about to change. For the better.

name: Will Buxton
tweet: For those banging the "its the car" drum, don't be surprised that the guy who has been doing incredible things in a Williams for two seasons, should be able to step up to a Mercedes and do incredible things...   The constant, in both cases, is the driver.  Bravo @GeorgeRussell63

name: Will Buxton
tweet: Oh @SChecoPerez you absolute beauty. As if you needed to show your class, your talent, your indisputable quality, you go and do it with by far and away your best drive in your best season. Incredible.
